<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-468-728  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 468 728.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  July 31 1989 v23 n31 p8(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Morris indicted in Internet virus affair. (Robert T. Morris Jr.;andO;includes related article on computer law)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Alexander, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Robert T. Morris Jr.andP;  is being indicted the week of Jul 20, 1989in US federal court in Syracuse, NY, with violating the ComputerFraud and Abuse Act of 1986.andP;  Morris is the alleged author of thecomputer virus, or worm program, that infiltrated the nationalInternet computer network beginning on Nov 2, 1989.andP;  He is thefirst defendant in a federal prosecution of a computer crimeinvolving a virus or worm and his is the first case under the 1986law.andP;  The law makes it a felony to intentionally access a federalinterest computer without authorization.andP;  Morris allegedlyparalyzed up to 6,200 university and military computers and causedsubstantial damage with a worm released from Cornell University.andO;Morris could receive a sentence of up to five years plus a$250,000 fine, and could be ordered to make restitution.andP;  Morrisplans to plead not guilty, his attorney says.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Statute:   Computer Fraud and Abuse Act of 1986 (interpretation andconstruction).andO;Topic:     Computer virusesCourtsInternet (Computer network).andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   Robert T. Morris Jr. (portrait)Person:    Morris, Robert T., Jr. (cases).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>